                    "text_V3dHLP": {
                      "type": "text",
                      "settings": {
                        "text": "<p>Sedums, also known as stonecrops, are among the most adaptable succulents, ranging from creeping groundcovers to upright perennials. With drought tolerance, colourful foliage, and star-shaped flowers that attract pollinators, they are excellent for pots, borders, rockeries, and green roofs in the UK. Their toughness and variety make them a favourite for both collectors and gardeners.<br/></p><h4><strong>Light</strong></h4><h2></h2><ul><li>Best in full sun for compact growth and vivid colour.<br/></li><li>Tolerates partial shade but may become leggy with fewer blooms.<br/></li><li>Ideal for rock gardens, dry walls, borders, or sunny containers.<br/></li></ul><h4><strong>Watering (3Ds Method: Drench, Drain, Dry)</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li>Water thoroughly, then allow excess to drain.<br/></li><li>Let soil dry fully before watering again.<br/></li><li>Hardy sedums in the ground often need little extra watering once established.<br/></li><li>Container sedums require more checks but still prefer drier conditions.<br/></li><li>Avoid constant dampness, which can lead to rot.<br/></li></ul><h4><strong>Soil and Repotting</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li>Use a <strong>free-draining mix</strong>: 1/3 John Innes no2 compost, 1/3 grit/perlite and 1/3 coconut coir.<br/></li><li>Avoid rich composts that cause floppy growth.<br/></li><li>Creeping sedums may need repotting every 2–3 years to refresh soil and manage spread.<br/></li></ul><h4><strong>Winter Care in the UK</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li>Many sedums are fully hardy and tolerate frost and snow.<br/></li><li>Evergreen types keep foliage year-round.<br/></li><li>Herbaceous types (e.g. Sedum 'Coca Cola') die back in winter and return in spring.<br/></li><li>Potted sedums benefit from shelter to prevent waterlogging.<br/></li></ul><h4><strong>Growth and Flowering</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li>Flower mainly in summer and autumn with star-shaped clusters<br/></li><li>Attract bees and butterflies with nectar-rich blooms.<br/></li><li>Flower colours include white, yellow, pink, and red.<br/></li><li>Creeping sedums flower earlier, upright forms later in the season.<br/></li></ul><h4><strong>Propagation</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li>Very easy to propagate by cuttings, division, or leaf pieces.<br/></li><li>Creeping sedums root wherever stems touch the soil.<br/></li><li>Upright sedums can be divided in spring for new clumps.<br/></li></ul><h4><strong>Common Issues</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li>Rot from poor drainage or overwatering.</li><li>Flopping stems in shade or nutrient-rich soils.<br/></li><li>Aphids may gather on flower heads but are easily managed.<br/></li></ul><h4><strong>Key Tips for UK Growers</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li>Groundcover sedums suit gravel gardens, troughs, and green roofs.<br/></li><li>Upright sedums add late-season colour to borders.<br/></li><li>Containers work well, especially mixed with other succulents.<br/></li><li>Minimal care needed: ensure sun, sharp drainage, and light feeding.</li></ul><p><br/>Sedums are some of the easiest and most rewarding succulents for UK gardens. With their toughness, wide variety, and pollinator-friendly blooms, they will thrive almost anywhere with sun and sharp drainage, rewarding you with reliable colour and structure year after year.</p>",
